Agoseris grandiflora var. grandiflora, Seeds connect to a flat receptacle at one end and fluffy pappus at the other.  The seed head can be 4" across.
Agoseris heterophylla var. cryptopleura, Yellow rays are much longer than phyllaries below.  Var. heterophylla 's rays are not.
Agoseris heterophylla var. cryptopleura, Basal leaves grow to 6" long and 1/2" wide.
Agoseris heterophylla var. cryptopleura, Pappus forms an open sphere.
Agoseris heterophylla var. heterophylla, Rays barely exceed the length of phyllaries .  Var. cryptopleura 's rays are much longer.
Agoseris heterophylla var. heterophylla, Basal leaves grow to 6" long.
Agoseris hirsuta, Many yellow ligulate ray flowers have flat tips.  There are no disc flowers .
Agoseris hirsuta, Green or purple phyllaries are much shorter than ray flowers .
Agoseris hirsuta, Basal Leaves are narrow, often with thin sideways lobes .  Single flowers grow at the top of an unbranching stalk.
Agoseris retrorsa, Several ranks of woolly phyllaries support a big (1" diameter) yellow flower head.
Agoseris retrorsa, Basal leaves , about 8" long, are narrow with many pairs of narrow, often backwards pointing, lobes .
Agoseris retrorsa, Short fruits with long beaks support lots of white pappus bristles, creating an open sphere up to 2" in diameter.
Chondrilla juncea, 9-12 yellow rays are surrounded by narrow, long green phyllaries .
Chondrilla juncea, The stem has stiff down-pointing hairs near its bottom.
Chondrilla juncea, An extensive root system generates a many-branched stem with flower-heads scattered among them.
Cichorium intybus, Petals have the same flat tips and serrations as other dandelions, but are blue.
Cichorium intybus, Long leaf-like bracts , widely spaced.
Cichorium intybus, Dandelion-like leaves.  Flowers emerge from along the stem as well as at the top.
Crepis bursifolia, Two rows of green phyllaries support about 50 yellow rays .
Crepis bursifolia, Basal leaves have many lateral lobes and one bigger terminal lobe.  Stem leaves smaller.
Crepis bursifolia, Each 1/4" fruit ends in a 1/2" beak which supports an inverted cone of  white bristly pappus .
Crepis vesicaria ssp. taraxacifolia, Beaked Hawksbeard has 10 to 20 dandelion heads, each at the top of its own branch.
Crepis vesicaria ssp. taraxacifolia, It does well in disturbed soil and is common along roadsides and paths.
Crepis vesicaria ssp. taraxacifolia, Basal leaves are deeply lobed , with a large lobe at the tip.  The hollow stem is ribbed, helping it stand erect
Hedypnois rhagadioloides, Many small dandelion flowers at the end of often limp stems.
Hedypnois rhagadioloides, Leaves are deep cut, like Common Dandelion, but with bristles.
Hedypnois rhagadioloides, Seeds have short, scaly pappus . Phyllaries open up, curve inward, and become woody.
Hieracium albiflorum, Look for several rows of white "petals" with flat serrated tips.  Note the yellow stamens.
Hieracium albiflorum, Hairy basal leaves are 3 to 6 inches long.
Hieracium albiflorum, This hawkweed has many branching flower heads at the top of a single stem.
Hypochaeris glabra, Red-tipped leaf-like phyllaries in several layers below the flower.
Hypochaeris glabra, Basal leaves are smooth, as opposed to that of Hairy Cat's Ear.
Hypochaeris glabra, Grows in dense patches.
Hypochaeris radicata, This dandelion-like flower is at the top of leafless, branching stems, 1 or 2 feet tall.
Hypochaeris radicata, Basal leaves have large, uneven "bites" taken out of them.
Hypochaeris radicata, Stems are tall, and branching.
Lactuca saligna, Heads with several yellow ligulate ray flowers grow along the stem.
Lactuca saligna, Stem leaves are quite narrow.  There are no basal leaves .
Lactuca saligna, Gives the appearance of a narrow flower with leaves an flowers close to the stem.
Lactuca serriola, Flowers are 1/2 inch across, with several layers of green[phyllaries]] behind them.
Lactuca serriola, Leaves are large at the bottom, with fine spines along the vein and edges.
Lactuca serriola, Seeds are fairly flat and brownish-grey.  Each connects to a beak that ends in a tuft .
Lactuca virosa, Yellow dandelion flower heads of about 15 rays appear on short stalks near the top of tis tall plant.
Lactuca virosa, Stem leaves are fairly wide, with sharp-toothed edges.  The underside of the central vein is often spiny, as shown here.
Lactuca virosa, If all the ray florets are pollinated, about 15 fruits grow a beak that connects to wide-spread white pappus .
Malacothrix californica, Red streaks decorate the back of yellow rays .  Green phyllaries are in two layers, the outer much shorter and with long tangled hairs.
Malacothrix californica, Outer rays are lighter in color and longer than others. Basal leaves are narrow and have long woolly hairs at their base.
Malacothrix californica, Pappus is a brush shape of fine white bristles.  Outer fruits have a shorter pappus.
Malacothrix coulteri, Like other Malcothrix , outer rays are longer than inner ones, forming a distinctive look.
Malacothrix coulteri, The flower head base is spherical, with many layers of overlapping short phyllaries , each with red center stripe.
Malacothrix coulteri, The pappus makes a thick brush of fine bristles of varying length.  Leaves are pointed and clasp the stem.
Malacothrix floccifera, A 1/2" flower head generally has white rays , often with a yellow center.  The back of the rays is often lavender.
Malacothrix floccifera, Leaves are woolly, with 4-6 pairs of roughly equal lobes .
Malacothrix floccifera, Pappus is a brush shape of fine white bristles.  Outer fruits have no pappus.
Microseris acuminata, A yellow flower head is surrounded by long, pointed inner phyllaries and very short, triangular outer phyllaries .
Microseris acuminata, Basal leaves are narrow, often with narrow sideways lobes .
Microseris acuminata, Needle Microseris has a distinctive seed head featuring long fruits and long, tapering scales tipped with bristles.
Microseris bigelovii, Rays may be yellow, orange, or a combination.  Green phyllaries are often purple tinged.
Microseris bigelovii, Long basal leaves form a rosette .  They have narrow, opposite, sideways lobes .
Microseris bigelovii, Each seed connects to several triangular scales that are tipped by a bristle, making a papery starburst.
Microseris campestris, Yellow rays and underlying (often purple) phyllaries are about the same length.
Microseris campestris, Basal leaves are narrow, with pinnate , pointed lobes .
Microseris campestris, Pappus is a 1" dia. papery starburst of scales tipped with long bristles.
Microseris douglasii ssp. douglasii, Much smaller than most other dandelions, it grows to about 6 inches tall.
Microseris douglasii ssp. douglasii, Notice the long single layer of green phyllaries wrapping the base of the flower.
Microseris douglasii ssp. douglasii, Basal leaves are long, but vary in shape.
Microseris douglasii ssp. tenella, A yellow or white flower head of many rays sits atop a bare stem. Basal leaves are narrow and rise from the ground.
Microseris douglasii ssp. tenella, Pappus forms an open sphere.  Unlike most Microseris , you hardly notice the papery scales.
Microseris douglasii ssp. tenella, A 1/4" long fruit has a tiny (1/25") scale tipped with 1/4" bristles.  Fruit tapers at the end.
Microseris elegans, Elegant Sliverpuffs has a rosette of basal leaves but no stem leaves.
Microseris elegans, Each pollinated ray flower develops a brown fruit tipped with a spiky pappus.
Microseris elegans, Similar to Short-Scaled Microseris, fruits support 5 tiny scales tipped with longer bristles.
Microseris sylvatica, Yellow rays are much longer than green phyllaries .  An outer layer of phyllaries is shorter, triangular, and becomes recurved.
Microseris sylvatica, Leaves are long (4-14"), basal , and, in some cases, along the stem.
Microseris sylvatica, Pappus is a large papery starburst, 1-2" dia.
Rafinesquia californica, About 20 rays form this white flower head which often shows a yellow center.  When it goes to seed it forms an open, fluffy sphere.
Rafinesquia californica, Below the head, ray flowers are purple marked.  Long, pointed phyllaries are surrounded by a calyculus of short triangular bracts.
Rafinesquia californica, Greyish green leaves have irregular lobes .  A few smaller, clasping leaves decorate the stem, which branches to several single flower heads at the top.
Sonchus asper ssp. asper, Sow Thistle has distinctive, long-spined leaves that wrap around the stem in a curlicue.
Sonchus asper ssp. asper, Flower heads bulge at the base, like a vase.
Sonchus asper ssp. asper, Sow Thistle has a thick, red stem, grows to over 3 feet tall, and branches to many flower heads at the top.
Sonchus oleraceus, Several yellow dandelion-like flower heads connect to the top of the stem.  The flower head base is vase shaped, with a wide bottom.
Sonchus oleraceus, Leaves are deeply lobed with small teeth at the margins.  They often end in a large arrowhead shape.
Sonchus oleraceus, After pollination, brown seeds mature on the flower head base and grow inverted cones of white bristles to help them fly away when they're mature.
Stebbinsoseris heterocarpa, White or yellow dandelion heads are small, about 1/2" across.  Each head sits atop a bare stem.
Stebbinsoseris heterocarpa, Basal leaves are linear, with thin, opposite lobes .
Stebbinsoseris heterocarpa, A pappus of scales connects to the fruit at one end and a bristle on the other.  It looks like a papery starburst.
Stephanomeria elata, Pink dandelion flower heads of about 6 rays connect directly to the stem.
Stephanomeria elata, Basal leaves are fairly narrow.  Stem leaves are tiny and easy to miss.
Stephanomeria elata, A cluster of plumose bristles grow from the tip of each fruit, creating a parachute to transport the seed when it's mature.
Stephanomeria exigua, A handful of white to pink rays are surrounded by an inner row of long, pointed phyllaries and an outer row of quite short phyllaries.
Stephanomeria exigua, Stem is wiry, often with spreading branches.  Flower heads grow near stem or in a branched array near the top of the plant.
Stephanomeria exigua, Few rays lead to few fruits and pappus parachutes, giving an open, bushy appearance.
Stephanomeria virgata ssp. pleurocarpa, Flower heads grow along stiff, vertical branches.  Although a dandelion, there are only a handful of rays .
Stephanomeria virgata ssp. pleurocarpa, In this subspecies, green phyllaries are appressed.  In ssp. virgata phyllaries are reflexed.
Stephanomeria virgata ssp. pleurocarpa, Each brown fruit grows a shock of plumose bristles to help the mature seed float away on the wind.
Taraxacum officinale, Here's the yellow dandelion head we all know.  Below are green phyllaries that point downward.
Taraxacum officinale, Leaves have irregular, backwards-pointing lobes .

Taraxacum officinale, Brown fruits are attached to a white oval receptacle at one end and grow a white beak at the other end.  The beak attaches to many bristles , forming a parachute that carries the seed when it's mature.
Tragopogon porrifolius, Purple dandelion ray flowers are framed by several narrow, pointed, green phyllaries.
Tragopogon porrifolius, A large sphere of pappus surrounds mature fruits.
Tragopogon porrifolius, Leaves are quite long, grasslike, and wrap around the stem.
Uropappus lindleyi, A small yellow flower head is nestled inside long, narrow, pointed, green phyllaries .
Uropappus lindleyi, Erect Stem to two feet with a single flower at the top.  Long narrow basal leaves.
Uropappus lindleyi, Rather than hairy bristles common on pappus , each fruit grows 5 papery scales to help it float away on the wind.
Arundo donax, Giant Reed is distinctive, growing to 30 feet on bamboo-like stems.  It has a silvery, hairy plume at the top.
Arundo donax, The stem is bamboo-like and is used to make structures, mats, and reeds for woodwind instruments.
Arundo donax, Leaf blades can grow many feet long.  They're flat or folded, with rough margins.
Vicia gigantea, Pea flowers (under 1" long) all hang off the same side of the flower stalk.  Black pea pods.
Vicia gigantea, Compound leaves are alternate and smooth-edged, with each leaflet about 1" long.
Vicia gigantea, Pea pods are over 1" long and turn black when mature.
Elymus condensatus, The inflorescence starts as a tight cylinder but opens up with branches, especially towards the bottom.
Elymus condensatus, Stems are thick, to 1/2" across.  5 to 35 spikelets grow out of each stem node .
Elymus condensatus, This is a tall rye.  Leaf blades have strong veins and grow to 1" wide and 24" long.  The top surface is smooth and the bottom rough.
Pentagramma triangularis, The broad triangle shape is rounded with two smaller segments that point down.
Pentagramma triangularis, The back of the fern is quite pale, often covered with a gold dusty substance that inhibits moisture loss.
Pentagramma triangularis, Each frond grows on a dark-brown shiny stalk, generally 8 - 12 inches long.
Heterotheca sessiliflora, Bright yellow, narrow ray flowers generally have space between them.  The center is tight with 30-50 disc flowers .
Heterotheca sessiliflora, Leaves get small near the top.  Several rows of phyllaries surround the flower head.  Leaves and phyllaries are covered with strong-smelling glandular hairs.
Heterotheca sessiliflora, Several bristly branches stand erect, branching into a flowering canopy at the top.
Eriophyllum confertiflorum, Golden Yarrow has clusters of yellow aster flowerheads at the tip of stems covered with feathery leaves.
Eriophyllum confertiflorum, Each flower head has several ray florets surrounding a half-sphere of tiny disc florets .
Eriophyllum confertiflorum, Leaves are quite narrow, making a thready appearance.
Lamarckia aurea, This grass is short and has distinctive, fluffy-looking, yellow or purple flowerheads. Leaves are about 3" long and flat.
Lamarckia aurea, Spikelets tend to stay on one side of the stem.  Woven florets are infertile.  1/4" awns come from fertile florets.
Lamarckia aurea, Inflorescences are shorter than your finger.  They can be purple or pale, golden yellow.
Lasthenia californica, 6 - 13 bright yellow petal-like ray flowers surround numerous tiny disk flowers .  Each disk flower has nectar to attract pollinators.
Lasthenia californica, Opposite leaves are narrow, sometimes with shallow lobes .  Solitary flowerheads grow at the tips of stems and side branches.
Lasthenia californica, Goldfields make quite a display, living up to their name.
Pinus sabiniana, Pale gray-green needles grouped in 3s are 8" to 12" long.
Pinus sabiniana, A heavy cone with upturned scales grows to 13 inches.
Pinus sabiniana, Does well in dry areas and is widespread in the Sierras and California foothills.
Grindelia camporum, About 30 yellow petals, with a yellow center.  Flower is fairly big - 1 to 3 inches across.
Grindelia camporum, Center of flower often filled with resin.  Note the reflexed green phyllaries.
Grindelia camporum, Leaves are stiff, but not fleshy.
Grindelia hirsutula, Flowerheads, up to 2 inches across, show many wide ray flowers and many central disk flowers .
Grindelia hirsutula, Hairy Gumweed grows several feet tall, with showy yellow flowerheads.  Early flowerheads show a white gummy resin.
Grindelia hirsutula, Below the flowerhead is a green spherical collection of overlapping phyllaries with reflexed tips.
Vicia villosa, This vetch has many large, hanging, pea flowers.  Colors vary from purples to pinks to white.
Vicia villosa, Flowers are tubular, ending in a pea-flower shape.  The deep colors catch your eye.
Vicia villosa, Winter vetch is a vine, draping itself over adjacent plants.
Luzula comosa var. comosa, This variety has long bracts that extend beyond the flower cluster.
Luzula comosa var. comosa, Like all Luzula rushes , leaves are flat and have long, soft, wavy hairs (thus Hairy Wood Rush).
Luzula comosa var. comosa, Stems are solid (unlike hollow grass stems).  They start out erect but can bend over from the weight of their flowers.
Phalaris aquatica, A dense cylinder of pale spikelets rises 2-6", and is less than 1" wide.  They're smooth to the touch.
Phalaris aquatica, Although the inflorescence looks like a spike , spikelets are connected on short stalks and have flat, reflective glumes .
Phalaris aquatica, Leaves are grey-green and droop at their ends.  Although impressive to look at, Harding Grass lives many years and is a troublesome weed, invading grasslands and disturbed areas.
Stachys ajugoides, Pink whorls of flowers mature from the bottom up.
Stachys ajugoides, A mint flower, with two upper lips and a tongue-like lower lip.
Stachys ajugoides, Whorls of flowers near the top.  Opposite leaves below.
Stachys rigida var. rigida, Flowers form in whorls around the upper stem, just above hairy opposite leaves.  The stem is square and also hairy.
Stachys rigida var. rigida, Flowers are pale pink with dark pink lines.  The upper lip is straight and the lower lip is bent back 90 degrees.
Stachys rigida var. rigida, Opposite leaves are thick and hairy and smell like mint when rubbed.  Leaf edges are serrated (and sometimes purple).
Ribes californicum var. californicum, A gorgeous hanging flower, with reflexed sepals , white petals, longer stamens and even longer pistils .
Ribes californicum var. californicum, Woody stems have 3 spines at each node .  Also emerging from each node are leaf, flower and fruit stalks.
Ribes californicum var. californicum, Fruits are translucent red spheres surrounded with spines .
Lithophragma heterophyllum, Tiny white flowers with 3-pointed petals grow on an erect stalk.  Roundish lobed leaves grow below.
Lithophragma heterophyllum, Each petal has a main point and two side points (sometimes more).
Lithophragma heterophyllum, Flowers are bell shaped, with the base covered by green or red sepals .
Rubus armeniacus, Flowers are about 1 inch wide, with 5 petals and many dark-tipped stamens.  Stout prickles .
Rubus armeniacus, Leaves are in patterns of 5 the first year, and in groups of 3 on second year side branches.
Rubus armeniacus, Stout prickles are spaced out on a thick (up to 1 inch wide) cane.  (Native blackberry has smaller prickles, closer together).
Trifolium campestre, Notice that older flowers turn brown and droop downward.
Trifolium campestre, Some leaves grow very near the flower.
Trifolium campestre, Full-looking flower heads, with more than 20 flowers in each.
Marrubium vulgare, Little white mint flowers grow in whorls above a cluster of spines. The spines protect the delicate flowers from herbivores.
Marrubium vulgare, Opposite leaves are pale and fuzzy, with a deeply wrinkled surface
Marrubium vulgare, Horehound grows erect in clumps in disturbed soil, often at the side of trails.
Erigeron canadensis, Neat phyllaries surround an aster-like flower head - a sign of a fleabane.
Erigeron canadensis, Alternate leaves 4 inches long and 1/2" wide.
Erigeron canadensis, Wide distinctive inflorescence with hundreds of composite flowers, growing to about 5 feet tall.
Adelinia grandis, Leaves are large, wide and long, like a hound's tongue.  Flowers appear in a loose cluster at the top of an erect stem.
Adelinia grandis, Flowers have 5 blue petals that surround 5 white nectaries .  They look similar to Forget-Me-Not, whose central appendages are yellow.
Adelinia grandis, Tiny nutlets grow in groups of 4, although they may not all develop.  They're covered in hooks to cling to passing animals.
Trifolium albopurpureum, Leaf-like green sepals surround purple and white petals.
Trifolium albopurpureum, Flowers and leaf stems can be 2 inches long, off the main stem.
Trifolium albopurpureum, Flowers and leaves are small.
Silene laciniata ssp. californica, Five brilliant red petals are deeply cut about 4 lobes , as if they'd been cut with pinking shears.
Silene laciniata ssp. californica, California Pink is low and spreading, with bright-red flowers standing up.
Silene laciniata ssp. californica, Leaves are narrow and opposite .  Flowers sit at the top of stems. Stamens and styles point upwards.
Pedicularis densiflora, This plant is an early springtime bloomer, finishing flowering before the trees above it grow their new leaves.
Pedicularis densiflora, Leaves are fern-like and alternate.  Yellow flower centers on a red background act as targets for pollinators.
Pedicularis densiflora, 1) Large upper lip.  2) Small white-tipped under lip. 3) Red leaf-like bracts .
Quercus berberidifolia, Leaves are fairly short, about 1 inch long.  They have holly-like toothed margins.
Quercus berberidifolia, The top surface has a polished appearance. The underside is pale and has short hairs. Veins run to the ends of the spiny teeth.
Quercus berberidifolia, An egg-shaped acorn sits in a short, warty acorn cap.
Juncus xiphioides, An open inflorescence , several inches tall, graces the top of the stem.  A green inflorescence bract extends beyond the top of the stem.
Juncus xiphioides, Like all rushes , it has small, 6-part flowers.  They're green, red or brown.  Several clusters of 3-10 flowers are separated by branched flower stalks.
Juncus xiphioides, Leaves start flat against each other, like iris leaves.  They rise about a foot, with their edges pointing toward the stem.
Festuca perennis, This grass stands erect and has spikelets alternating up the stem, 2-ranked .
Festuca perennis, Notice how each spikelet fits in an indentation in the stem. Mature anthers show here, spreading their pollen on the wind.
Festuca perennis, Spikelets have quite a few florets . Awn length varies - long here and absent in the previous picture.
Carduus pycnocephalus, Leaves are fairly flat with spiny, wavy margins.
Carduus pycnocephalus, Stems have spiny wings along their length.
Carduus pycnocephalus, Italian Thistles produce hundreds of seeds which grow readily in grasslands, often outcompeting native grasses.
Triteleia laxa, 6 stamens have blue anthers .  Petal-like tepals show a darker central vein.
Triteleia laxa, Flowers stalks are fairly long (to 3").  The similar-looking Blue Dicks has flowers clustered tightly together.
Triteleia laxa, The inflorescence is an umbel , with flower stalks like the spokes of an umbrella.
Pseudognaphalium luteoalbum, Flowers bunched together with pink or red centers
Pseudognaphalium luteoalbum, Woolly leaves
Pseudognaphalium luteoalbum, Grows erect in clusters.
Salsola soda, Fleshy thin leaves.
Salsola soda, Green or red stems.
Salsola soda, Grows to a bit over 2 feet tall, generally in wet areas.
Micranthes californica, Five white petals, red-tipped stamens, green center.
Micranthes californica, Basal leaves have stems, or oval, and often have teeth or lobes.
Micranthes californica, Plant is about 1 foot tall, with basal leaves and flowers at the top.
Solanum nigrum, Petals recurve back, highlighting the yellow center.  This is a pattern for all nightshades.
Solanum nigrum, Flowers are in small groups, each at the end of its own stalk ( pedicel ).
Solanum nigrum, These immature berries will turn red and then black as they mature.
Sabulina pusilla, Tiny flower has white petals separated by green sepals .  Sometimes the white petals are missing.
Sabulina pusilla, Flower at the end of the stem, with a green and white center.
Sabulina pusilla, This tiny plant is only 2 inches tall.  Leaves are short and thin.
Cryptantha flaccida, This small annual flower has several spikes of tiny flowers at the top of the stem.
Cryptantha flaccida, Flowers have 5 white petals around a central cavity that contains a nutlet.
Cryptantha flaccida, The petals and nutlet are protected by green, hairy bracts .
Carex serratodens, The female pistil is protected by a hard, green perigynium .  Male anthers form a separate cluster, above.
Carex serratodens, The fruit develops inside the perigynium with the stigma lobes remaining, looking like 2 teeth - thus the name.
Carex serratodens, Leaves and stem are blue-green.  Always found near water.
Lewisia rediviva var. rediviva, Many pink petals, paler in the center.  Lots of yellow-tipped stamens and a pale pink pistil .
Lewisia rediviva var. rediviva, Stems are short.  Below the petals are 6-9 oval sepals .
Lewisia rediviva var. rediviva, Basal leaves are bean shaped, and form a rosette under this low-growing plant.
Eschscholzia californica, Thin orange petals overlap each other.  Notice the sheath covering the young bud.  Petals close at night and open in the morning.
Eschscholzia californica, Leaves are grey-green and are much divided.  The round flat base just below the petals is distinctive and edged in rose-pink.
Eschscholzia californica, Across the state, California Poppies fill grassy areas with an orange display from April to July.
Artemisia californica, Sagebrush starts branching right at the ground, creating a thick dome shape.
Artemisia californica, Leaves are very narrow and aromatic.  Super tiny flowers cluster in a bowl of phyllaries .
Artemisia californica, Sagebrush is often paler than the vegetation around it.
Trifolium hybridum, A traditional spherical clover flower head, in pink and white, turning brown with age.
Trifolium hybridum, Leaves in 3s, with no markings.  Tiny serrations along the edge.
Trifolium hybridum, Flowers are on long stalks ( pedicels ).  The plant can grow over 1 foot tall.
Agoseris grandiflora, Many (over 100) ray flowers are densely packed. Stamen columns are often reddish brown.
Agoseris grandiflora, Several layers of red-purple rounded leaf-like phyllaries surround the flower.  Note the white soft hair at the base.
Agoseris grandiflora, Seeds connect to a flat receptacle . Long white beaks end in tufts to form a big, fluffy sphere, reaching 2" in diameter.
Pellaea mucronata, Leaflets are separate from each other, and curled under along the edges.
Pellaea mucronata, Underside of leaflet has brown sporangia.
Pellaea mucronata, Frond is triangular in shape, with separate leaflets often looking dented from above.
Cirsium quercetorum, Brown flower color.
Cirsium quercetorum, Leaves puckered, with long spines
Cirsium quercetorum, Grows low to the ground.
Marah fabacea, This is a vine with many small white-yellow flowers of 5 or 6 petals.  Fruit is a sphere with prickles .
Marah fabacea, Many tendrils off the stem make it a great climber.
Marah fabacea, Fruit is large, about 2 inches across, with thin prickles .
Melica californica, California Melic is an erect plant with ascending, flat leaves. Spikelets lie close to the stem, making a narrow cylinder.
Melica californica, Melica spikelets are oval and cylindrical, not flattened like most other grasses.  Each spikelet has 2-5 florets .  At maturity, anthers emerge to release pollen on the wind.
Melica californica, Thin spikelet branches run along the stem. Glumes at the base of each spikelet are papery and become purple with time.  There are no awns .
Plantago erecta, This plant is smaller than other plantains, perhaps 4 inches tall.  It has long, narrow erect leaves.
Plantago erecta, Tiny 4-petaled flowers form a tight cluster at the top of the stem.
Plantago erecta, California Plantain can grow in dense patches.
Sidalcea malviflora, Five pink petals with radiating lines on each petal.
Sidalcea malviflora, Basal leaves round and not deeply cut.
Sidalcea malviflora, Deeply cut leaves.
Stellaria media, 5 deeply lobed white petals often look like 10.  Green pointed sepals between the petals.
Stellaria media, Opposite leaves are oval and come to a point.
Stellaria media, Grows to a foot or so.  Lies along the ground in dense mats.
Acmispon wrangelianus, Single yellow pea flowers are small, less than 1/2" long.  Leaves and stems have soft hairs.
Acmispon wrangelianus, Leaflets are in asymmetrical groups of four.  Pea pods have a curved beak at their tips.
Acmispon wrangelianus, The stem branches near its base.  Single flowers and pea pods grow from leaf axils .
Galium porrigens, Look for whorled leaves in groups of 4, small yellow flowers with 4  petals, a square stem, and white berries.
Galium porrigens, Petals are only 1/2" long, but flowers are even smaller, about 1/10" across.
Galium porrigens, Flowers are tiny but showy, with red and yellow parts.
Agoseris apargioides var. apargioides, The flower head is of medium size, about 3/4".  Many yellow rays often have purple markings underneath.
Agoseris apargioides var. apargioides, Basal leaves lie flat against the ground in a rosette.  They're often hairy.

Matricaria discoidea, The flower head is made up of many tiny flowers with no petals.

Festuca arundinacea, Spikelets start out gathered tightly around a stem and branch out as they mature.  They're often tinged purple.
Festuca arundinacea, Long leaves have prominent parallel veins.  Blade edges are rough and have some hairs.  Like all fescues , the leaf sheath is open and the collar is hairless.
Juncus patens, Branched flower clusters appear to come from the side of the stem.  Fruits are red or brown.
Juncus patens, Grey-green stems rise up  from leaf sheaths that start brown and become pale.  There are no leaf blades .
Juncus patens, Found in marshes, creeks and seeps.
Carex densa, Separate male and female flowers form a dense head at the tip of a rough (scabrous) triangular stem.  Narrow bracts grow at the base of the inflorescence .
Carex densa, Flowers turn brown at maturity.  Leaves grow to 20". The leaf sheath is often wrinkled.
Carex densa, This low-growing sedge is found in wet meadows, springs and shores.  Floral stems are generally taller than the leaves.
Trifolium dubium, Flower head made up of fewer than 20 flowers.
Trifolium dubium, Flowers are yellow, becoming brown and drooping with age, the same as Hop Clover.
Trifolium dubium, This plant is maturing, with flowers falling apart and becoming brown.
Carex subbracteata, This medium-tall sedge has a very small inflorescence , about 1" tall.  It often leans on adjacent plants.
Carex subbracteata, The inflorescence is wedge-shaped and includes separate male and female florets , each covered by a small bract.
Carex subbracteata, Bracts turn brown or sometimes coppery, with a pale or green center.
Sidalcea malviflora ssp. laciniata, Like other checkerblooms, petals show different-colored veins and have squared-off, slightly notched petals.
Sidalcea malviflora ssp. laciniata, This subspecies has deep, irregular cuts in its leaves.  Lower leaves are about 2" across.
Sidalcea malviflora ssp. laciniata, Pink-lavender petals are generally separate to their base. Upper leaves are dissected into linear segments.
Stachys rigida var. quercetorum, An upper lobe protects reproductive parts and a lower lobe provides a landing spot for pollinators.
Stachys rigida var. quercetorum, Opposite leaves have rounded toothed edges, prominent veins and a wide base.
Stachys rigida var. quercetorum, Flowers cluster in whorls along the stem.
Plectritis congesta ssp. brachystemon, Erect, slender stems have opposite leaves and end in a tight cluster of pink, violet or white flowers.
Plectritis congesta ssp. brachystemon, Each flower is tiny.  A tubular base opens up into 5 lobes of different sizes.
Plectritis congesta ssp. brachystemon, Lower leaves are spoon-shaped with smooth margins.
Nemophila heterophylla, This plant, under 5" tall, shows a small, beautiful white flower over opposite , lobed leaves.
Nemophila heterophylla, The tiny flower, less than 1/2", shows dark anthers inside a white cup.  It sits in a green, hairy calyx .
Nemophila heterophylla, Lower leaves are opposite and deeply lobed .  Upper leaves are not always opposite and are smaller and less divided.
Plectritis macrocera, Flowers tightly grouped, each a short trumpet with 5 petals.
Plectritis macrocera, Flowers have a short spur at their base,  They grow along the stem and at the top.
Plectritis macrocera, Opposite leaves, up to 2 inches long.  Grows erect to 2 or 3 feet.
Triphysaria versicolor ssp. faucibarbata, Flowers are white or yellow, growing in a dense spike at the top of stems that grow to about 2 feet.
Triphysaria versicolor ssp. faucibarbata, Leaves are about 3 inches long, divided into a few narrow, pointed lobes.
Triphysaria versicolor ssp. faucibarbata, Covers moist grassy hillsides in the spring.
Boykinia occidentalis, A loose cluster of tiny white star-like flowers inspires its common name, Brook Foam.
Boykinia occidentalis, At the base, large, roundish, irregularly toothed leaves (up to 4") grow on hairy stalks.
Boykinia occidentalis, The cup-shaped base of each flower can be white or pale red.
Notholithocarpus densiflorus, Look for a leathery leaf with many strong veins, each leading to a point on the edge of the leaf.  Edges  are often curled under.
Notholithocarpus densiflorus, The underside of the leaf is often fuzzy, a good quick ID characteristic.
Notholithocarpus densiflorus, Acorn tops are woody, covered with slender scales that point outwards and recurve.
Clematis vitalba, This vigorous vine drapes over plants.  Its showy seeds make it easy to spot.
Clematis vitalba, Heart shaped leaves, roughly serrated.
Clematis vitalba, Grooved stem.  Opposite leaves.
Rhododendron occidentale, Fragrant flowers about 2 inches across, often with yellow on the inside.
Rhododendron occidentale, Leaves about an inch wide and 4 inches long.
Rhododendron occidentale, Shrub, grows to 16 feet tall.
Euonymus occidentalis, Bright red 3-part fruits are conspicuous in the late summer.
Euonymus occidentalis, Leaves are narrow and pointed, and are arranged in opposite pairs
Euonymus occidentalis, Small brown or pink flowers are about 1/4" across and have nectar in the center.

captions: Polystichum munitum, Notice the little sword hilts pointing down at the base of each leaflet. Fronds are thick, dark green and evergreen .
Polystichum munitum, Under the fronds are round sori , full of spores, lined adjacent to the center line.
Polystichum munitum, Sword Fern is common in acidic soil under redwoods and other damp shady places.  Its base is round and its fronds arch upward.
Ceanothus decornutus, Flowers have 5 petals, rather than 6, as with Jepsonii.
Ceanothus decornutus, While leaves are similar to C. jepsonii, flowers are paler.
Ceanothus decornutus, Found on exposed serpentinite outcrops on Nicasio Ridge.
Blennosperma nanum var. nanum, Many yellow petals.  Note ring of white stigmas.  Buds are covered with green bracts.
Blennosperma nanum var. nanum, Yellow petals are separate from each other, with green bracts below each one.
Blennosperma nanum var. nanum, Leaves are thin but fleshy.
Eriophyllum lanatum var. arachnoideum, Yellow center and many yellow petals (ray flowers).  Grows to 2 feet high.
Eriophyllum lanatum var. arachnoideum, Several flowers grow out of a base of woolly leaves.  Leaves have thin finger-like lobes .
Eriophyllum lanatum var. arachnoideum, Phyllaries are also woolly, and are pointed.
Hemizonia congesta ssp. lutescens, The flowerhead center is flat, showing a circle of tiny disc flowers . Outer ray flowers have 3 lobes at the tip.
Hemizonia congesta ssp. lutescens, Yellow ray flowers lay flat, in plane.  They're a favorite of native bees.  Green phyllaries below the flowerhead form a single row.
Hemizonia congesta ssp. lutescens, In the summer and fall, Tarweed fills fields with color and its distinctive tarry smell.
Calystegia subacaulis ssp. subacaulis, Flowers grow on 1 inch stalks, above a rosette of basal leaves .
Calystegia subacaulis ssp. subacaulis, Morning Glory flowers open in the morning and wither by the end of the day.
Calystegia subacaulis ssp. subacaulis, Leaves grow on 1" stalks.  They're shaped like an arrow head, with a wide base and pointed tip.
Eriogonum nudum var. nudum, Stems have no leaves (thus nudum ).  Stems are topped with rounded clusters of pale flowers.
Eriogonum nudum var. nudum, Clusters of tiny flowers have long stamens sticking out.  Flowers show white, pale pink or yellow.
Eriogonum nudum var. nudum, Leaves are on long stalks at the base of the plant.  They're grey-green above; white-hairy underneath.  They have a prominent central vein.
Trifolium gracilentum, Base of petals dark pink-purple, fading to white-pink at the end.  Note there are no bracts below the flower.
Trifolium gracilentum, Leaves have small serrations.
Trifolium gracilentum, Flowers and leaves are small, (thus pin-point) even though the plant stands erect.
Pseudognaphalium ramosissimum, Pink or white papery phyllaries surround white or yellow flower centers.
Pseudognaphalium ramosissimum, Flower branch near the top of the stem.
Pseudognaphalium ramosissimum, Grows to 4 feet tall, in bunches.
Polypodium calirhiza, Fronds have broad oval segments coming to a dull point.  Segments get shorter close to the base.
Polypodium calirhiza, A small fern, 4 to 10 inches long.
Polypodium calirhiza, Groups together on rocky banks.
Castilleja exserta ssp. exserta, Each flower is tubular, ending in  3 white and purple sacs below and a narrow beak on top, creating an owl's face.
Castilleja exserta ssp. exserta, Leaves are narrow and hairy. Bracts around the flowers are narrow and hairy, with lavender tips.
Castilleja exserta ssp. exserta, Purple Owl's Clover is found on grassy hillsides, especially in serpentine soils.
Centaurea calcitrapa, Look for a purple-pink thistle flower with radial needles pointing straight out below it.
Centaurea calcitrapa, Stems are grooved.  This plant grows as a dense shrub.
Centaurea calcitrapa, Radial basal leaves have deeply indented lobes .
Ceanothus cuneatus var. ramulosus, Flowers have 5 petals with yellow-topped stamens sticking out.
Ceanothus cuneatus var. ramulosus, Leaves are thick, fairly short, and round edged.
Ceanothus cuneatus var. ramulosus, Prodigious blooms created by thousands of flowers on a single bush.
Ceanothus foliosus var. foliosus, Indigo Brush produces large numbers of small flowers and leaves.
Ceanothus foliosus var. foliosus, Tiny flowers gather in small clumps, with white and yellow accents.
Ceanothus foliosus var. foliosus, Tiny leaves are thick and have distinctive glandular bumps.
Notholithocarpus densiflorus var. densiflorus, Leaf has strong veins, each leading to a point on the edge of the leaf.
Notholithocarpus densiflorus var. densiflorus, Underside of leaf is often fuzzy.
Notholithocarpus densiflorus var. densiflorus, Acorns tops look like wild hair.
Calystegia purpurata ssp. purpurata, Petals fuse to each other in an open funnel shape.  They're white to pink, with darker lines near the folds.
Calystegia purpurata ssp. purpurata, Leaves are thin and heart-shaped, ending in a point.  Margins are smooth.
Calystegia purpurata ssp. purpurata, Vine Morning Glory runs along the ground and climbs up other plants. This species is not hairy.
Triteleia peduncularis, 6 white petal-like tepals surround a yellow style and white-tipped stamens (the ones in the picture are old).
Triteleia peduncularis, Flowers form an umbel at the top of a branchless stalk (a scape) that rises from the ground.
Triteleia peduncularis, Leaves are quite long (4-12") and narrow (1/4").  The back of the tepals often have a violet flush.
Hesperolinon congestum, Pink buds open to nearly white flowers, about 1/2" across.  Pink-tipped stamens stand out from the petals. Sepals are hairy.
Hesperolinon congestum, Flat-topped flower clusters appear at the tips of many branches.
Hesperolinon congestum, Leaves are alternate , linear and not hairy.  They have glandular stipules that exude a protective red resin.
Toxicoscordion fontanum, Marsh Zigadene has many flowers, generally smaller than 1/2" across.
Toxicoscordion fontanum, It also has many narrow basal leaves.
Toxicoscordion fontanum, Fruits are capsules.  When dry, they open along their length to release many seeds.
Calochortus umbellatus, This pale lilac-pink flower is about 1-1/2" across, with purple spots at the center. Anthers can be light blue or pink.
Calochortus umbellatus, A single basal leaf and smaller stem leaves photosynthesize  sugars needed to create one or more showy flowers, each on its own stalk.
Calochortus umbellatus, Seed capsules hang down from the withering plant.  When mature, they'll drop to the ground and germinate when exposed to cold, moist conditions.
Allium lacunosum var. lacunosum, Flowers have 6 petal-like tepals with stamens growing directly out of them.  Dark veins point toward nectaries , attracting pollinators.
Allium lacunosum var. lacunosum, Flower stalks form a dense umbel , with 2 bracts at the base of the umbel.
Allium lacunosum var. lacunosum, Stems are thick and wavy, up to 1 foot tall.  Leaves are long, thin and hollow, and have an onion smell.
Calandrinia menziesii, This flower has 5 dark pink petals, yellow-tipped stamens , and is less than 1" wide.  Leaves are thick and edible.
Calandrinia menziesii, Leaves are alternate , thick, fairly long, and wider towards the tip.
Calandrinia menziesii, Red Maids needs wet conditions to germinate and start growing, but does well in full sun and gravelly soil after that.
Eriogonum luteolum var. caninum, Pink flowers are tiny, with 6 segments and long stamens .
Eriogonum luteolum var. caninum, Stems branch frequently, with spherical flower clusters at each tip.
Eriogonum luteolum var. caninum, Leaves are mostly basal , roundish and on stalks.  They're densely hairy underneath and generally nearly hairless above.
Calochortus tiburonensis, Petals often face the sky, revealing distinctive maroon markings.  Their pale color tends to blend in with tall grasses around them.
Calochortus tiburonensis, Petals are hairy.  6 red-brown anthers surround a 3- lobed style .
Calochortus tiburonensis, This showy lily grows natively only on Ring Mountain.
Delphinium hesperium ssp. hesperium, 5 petal-like sepals surround a smaller corolla made up of 4 petals and a long spur.  The flower is hairy on the inside.
Delphinium hesperium ssp. hesperium, Flowers form a spike at the top of a single stem.  New flowers emerge at the top while older flowers mature below.
Delphinium hesperium ssp. hesperium, Leaves are deeply divided.
Lomatium dasycarpum ssp. dasycarpum, Clusters of yellowish-green flowers grow on thick stalks.  The flower clusters grow in an umbrella pattern (an umbel ).
Lomatium dasycarpum ssp. dasycarpum, Leaves are finely dissected.
Lomatium dasycarpum ssp. dasycarpum, Flowers turn into clusters of flat, round seeds.
Perideridia kelloggii, Rounded clusters of small flowers sit on stalks that join at a point, like an umbrella.
Perideridia kelloggii, Leaflets near the base of the plant are long and narrow and often forked.  Flowers and fruits are tiny and beautiful.
Perideridia kelloggii, Yampah grows in grasslands, often in serpentine soils.
Poa bulbosa ssp. vivipara, Bulbous Blue Grass has an odd-looking inflorescence composed mostly of small, brown, sprouting bulblets.
Poa bulbosa ssp. vivipara, This grass is easy to spot once you know what you're looking for: brown blobs where you'd expect to see grass florets .
Poa bulbosa ssp. vivipara, Unlike other grasses, the stem grows from a small bulb.
Koeleria macrantha, Developing spikelets look like a spike until they open up at maturity.  This grass is excellent food for wildlife and livestock.
Koeleria macrantha, At maturity, alternating branches hold several spikelets each.
Koeleria macrantha, Narrow ascending leaves are mostly basal , with a few leaves at mid-stem.  They become inrolled when they dry.
Streptanthus glandulosus ssp. pulchellus, Flower base puffy and hairy, with four little petals at the end.
Streptanthus glandulosus ssp. pulchellus, Flowers at the top of the stem.
Streptanthus glandulosus ssp. pulchellus, Fruit is narrow, stands out from the stem, and is hairy.
Delphinium nudicaule, Trumpet-like larkspur flowers can be red or orange.
Delphinium nudicaule, Flower stalks ( pedicels )for each flower.  Leaves have deep cuts.
Delphinium nudicaule, Flowers on very thin stems.
Carduus pycnocephalus ssp. pycnocephalus, Spines are prominent along the stem and leaves. Each seed has a pappus parachute.
Raphanus sativus, Radish flowers have 4 paddle-like  petals with a bright yellow center.
Raphanus sativus, Leaves are pinnate , divided with the largest lobe at the end.
Raphanus sativus, These distinctive flowers are widespread in moist, disturbed soil.
Luzula comosa, Wood Rush is easy to spot, standing erect with wide, grass-like leaves and green/brown flower clusters.
Luzula comosa, Flowers are in tight bunches, each with 6 tepals , surrounded with fibrous bracts .
Luzula comosa, Leaves in the Luzula genus are wide and have long, soft, wavy hairs.
Stachys rigida, This Mint family flower has a small hood covering reproductive organs and a large lip hanging below.
Stachys rigida, Up to six flowers grow in a whorl at leaf axils on the upper stem.  Leaves are opposite, crinkly, and have scalloped edges.  They can grow to 5 inches long.
Stachys rigida, Hedge Nettle grows in tight communities of upright plants.
Hordeum brachyantherum, Arching inflorescences flatten and turn purple at maturity, with spikelets opening up but still connected directly to the stem.
Hordeum brachyantherum, Young spikelets form a dense cylinder.  They connect in groups of 3.
Hordeum brachyantherum, Meadow Barley Grass is widespread in pastures, meadows and stream banks.
Vicia villosa ssp. varia, The first thing you'll notice about this vetch is the large, dense cluster pea flowers.  Colors vary from purples to pinks to whites.
Vicia villosa ssp. varia, Each pea flower has a calyx cap at the top, with narrow sepal fingers sticking out.
Vicia villosa ssp. varia, Smooth Vetch grows rapidly and climbs over other plants to reach the sun and pollinators.
Foeniculum vulgare, Carrot-top umbrella-shaped flowers.
Foeniculum vulgare, Finely divided leaves
Foeniculum vulgare, Often found beside pathways and roads.
Erodium moschatum, Flowers are less than 1" across, with a typical geranium lavender color.
Erodium moschatum, Plants start with a rosette of white-stemmed leaves with bigger leaflets than Red-Stemmed Filaree.
Erodium moschatum, Fruits have a beak over 1", which twists into a spiral when wet, helping it drill into the ground.
Oxalis pes-caprae, 5 bright-yellow petals overlap, showing a green center.
Oxalis pes-caprae, 3 heart-shaped leaflets are thin and taste acidic if you eat them.
Oxalis pes-caprae, In early spring, Sourgrass and mustard make large patches of yellow in fields.
Layia chrysanthemoides, Individual flowers at the top of stems.  White tips are often indented.
Layia chrysanthemoides, 5 - 18 yellow petals, often with white tips.
Layia chrysanthemoides, Common in grassy meadows at low elevations, although it can be found up to 6,500 feet.
Lupinus albifrons var. douglasii, The erect stem and leaves are covered in silvery hairs.  Pea flowers mature from the bottom up.
Lupinus albifrons var. douglasii, A column of pea flowers can grow to 12" long.  Yellow or white banner spots age to purple.
Lupinus albifrons var. douglasii, This coastal shrub is found inland of coastal dunes in the Bay Area south to the Channel Islands.
Hypericum concinnum, 5 yellow petals that fold back.  Many long stamens .
Hypericum concinnum, Opposite leaves grow regularly up the stem.
Hypericum concinnum, Clusters of plants grow to a few feet tall.
Calystegia occidentalis ssp. occidentalis, This  morning glory flower is about 1.5 inches wide, showing rib marks where the petals fuse.  It turns purple with age.
Calystegia occidentalis ssp. occidentalis, Leaves are alternate, and under 2 inches long, shaped like thin arrow heads.
Calystegia occidentalis ssp. occidentalis, This vine can grow along the ground or climb whatever's around.
Lupinus albifrons var. albifrons, Flowers are arranged in an open column. They have a pale banner spot that turns purple with age.
Lupinus albifrons var. albifrons, Leaves are palmate (finger-like).  They're covered in dense, silvery hair.
Lupinus albifrons var. albifrons, Flower spikes can be up to 12 inches tall.  Notice the woody branches.
Piperia transversa, This orchid flower has a spur that holds pollen.  Night moths uncoil their tongues to reach it,  rubbing against the plant's reproductive parts.
Piperia transversa, The spur is distinctive - flat and horizontal.  Petals and sepals have green veins.
Piperia transversa, A single stem grows 6 to 20" tall. 2 to 5 basal leaves have parallel veins.
Phacelia hastata var. compacta, Flower coils like a fuzzy caterpillar.
Phacelia hastata var. compacta, Individual flowers have 5 white petals with many long stamens.
Phacelia hastata var. compacta, Found in dry rocky areas.
Senecio integerrimus, Tall stem.  Flowers bunched at the top.
Senecio integerrimus, Lower leaves larger, occasional up the stem.
Senecio integerrimus, Fuzzy leaves bumpy near the base and smoother near the end.
Astragalus oophorus var. oophorus, Small, oval leaflets line compound leaves .  They connect alternately to rather thick, decumbent branches.
Astragalus oophorus var. oophorus, Pea flowers have purple recurved banners and white keels that turn ivory with age.
Astragalus oophorus var. oophorus, Brilliantly colored pea pods are puffed up like a bladder.  Tiny peas line their inner ridges.
Psathyrotes annua, In the aster family, many tiny flowers are surrounded by a set of pale hairy phyllaries .
Psathyrotes annua, Flower are sometimes reddish purple.
Psathyrotes annua, Leaves create a low mounded cushion. They're quite hairy, which gives the plant a pale appearance.
Eriogonum ampullaceum, Flowers are white with red parts.  They cluster closely together next to the stem.
Eriogonum ampullaceum, Leaves are basal, rounded, and wooly, up to 1 inch wide.
Eriogonum ampullaceum, Grows to about 2 feet tall.  Stem is not hairy.
Eleocharis montevidensis, 30 to 100 dark scales form a dense spike of bisexual spikelets less than 1/2" long at the top of the stem.  A green bract extends beyond the spikelet cluster.
Eleocharis montevidensis, Hidden behind the scales are bisexual flowers.  The base of the female style has a bump on it called a tubercle .
Eleocharis montevidensis, This spike rush is a sedge , not a rush . Leaves are dark sheaths only - there are no leaf blades .  Unlike most sedges, stems of this species are oval, not triangular.
Lomatium macrocarpum, Balls of flowers spread out above a bed of leaves on this low-growing plant.
Lomatium macrocarpum, Compound leaves are grey, hairy, and can grow to 6 inches long.  They're divided into many segments.
Lomatium macrocarpum, Leaves and flowers are on long, densely-hairy stalks.  The flat fruit looks a bit like a sunflower seed.
Arnica discoidea, Toothed leaves have a wide base and a pointed tip. Yellow composite flowers with no "petals" ( ray flowers ).
Arnica discoidea, Disk flowers cluster in a head above white pappus and green phyllaries .
Arnica discoidea, This hairy plant grows to about 2 feet tall.
Brodiaea coronaria, Bright purple tepals (petals) have a darker central vein.  In the center, 3 fertile stamens alternate with 3 infertile stamens that look like small white petals.
Brodiaea coronaria, Flowers grow on stalks that are longer than the flower is tall.
Phoradendron leucarpum ssp. tomentosum, Mistletoe grows primarily in oak trees, forming roughly 3 foot clusters of different colored leaves.
Phoradendron leucarpum ssp. tomentosum, Leaves are thick and opposite .  Small berries are pinkish-white.
Phoradendron leucarpum ssp. tomentosum, Flowers, and later berries, grow on spikes starting a leaf joints.
Ceanothus incanus, Many flowers cluster in an aromatic plume, attracting a wide array of bees, crawling insects, hummingbirds and butterflies.
Ceanothus incanus, Wide leaves are green on top and paler underneath, with short hairs lying flat along the leaf bottom.
Ceanothus incanus, Coast Whitethorn is an erect, open shrub with arching, rigid branches and whitish bark.  Twigs sometimes end in thorns.
Stachys bullata, Opposite fuzzy leaves
Stachys bullata, Square stem with flowers in whorls
Stachys bullata, Flowers at the top of stems.
Clinopodium douglasii, Good smelling leaves on this low-growing herb are thick, have toothed edges and are opposite each other along the length of the stem.
Clinopodium douglasii, Small pale lavendar mint flowers grow on stalks from the leaf axils of the opposite leaves, making opposite flowers.
Clinopodium douglasii, Many square-stemmed Yerba Buena plants trail along the ground, combining to form an aromatic ground cover.
Polystichum dudleyi, Dudley's Sword Fern (pale green here) has divided segments .  Western Sword Fern (dark green) does not.
Polystichum dudleyi, Like Sword Fern, each segment has a "thumb" at its base.  The brown circles are sori , filled with spores for reproduction.
Polystichum dudleyi, This handsome fern does well in moist, acidic, redwood forests.
Arctostaphylos pajaroensis, Clusters of small, pink, urn-shaped flowers hang down from branch tips.
Arctostaphylos pajaroensis, Young leaves are red, turning green as they grow thicker.
Navarretia squarrosa, Small  trumpet flowers have five 1/10" lobes that open up at the top. Stamens and pistil stay inside the trumpet.
Navarretia squarrosa, Flowers cluster in a 1" ball, surrounded by spikey bracts .
Navarretia squarrosa, Stem is erect, 1 - 2 feet tall. Alternate leaves are feathery.  Smell this plant if you dare!
Agoseris apargioides, Outer petals often have a purple tinge on the bottom.  Flower base is rounded.  Green [[phyllaries[[ are short and round-tipped.
Agoseris apargioides, Basal rosette of leaves.
Agoseris apargioides, Often found in coastal sand dunes.
Astragalus nuttallii, Yellow pea flowers are arranged in a tight spiral.
Astragalus nuttallii, Compound leaves are pinnate , like all vetches. They're large and hairy.
Astragalus nuttallii, The fruit blows up into a huge bladder.
Juncus balticus, Flowers cluster at the top of the stem, with a stem-like bract extending above.  Note the slightly different color of the bract.
Juncus balticus, This closeup shows brown tepals , yellow anthers on short filaments , and pink stigmas over a superior ovary .
Juncus balticus, This rush has no leaf blade , just a brown sheath that covers the green stem.
Sidalcea glaucescens, Dark pink flower with 5 thin, overlapping petals .
Sidalcea glaucescens, Leaves are deeply divided, often into 5 parts.  Flowers grow along the stem.
Sidalcea glaucescens, Notice sepals below the petals, twisted petals of a bloom not yet open, and the large reproductive parts in the center of the flower.
Asclepias cordifolia, Purple-petaled flowers cluster on stalks up to 2" long, forming a loose sphere.
Asclepias cordifolia, Purple petals are spread wide or back.  5 circular attachments called hoods protect the stamens .
Asclepias cordifolia, Leaves are large and heart-shaped, clasping the stem.
Lupinus arbustus, Look for an obvious spur (the bump on the left side of the pea flower in this drawing).
Lupinus arbustus, Leaves are palmate (narrow and finger like).
Lupinus arbustus, Flowers stand erect over the leaves.  Can be white or blue.
Muilla maritima, Long narrow leaves surround a stalk that grows over 1 foot to an umbel of 6-petaled white flowers.
Muilla maritima, Flowers are under 1/2 inch across and have 6 petal-like tepals .
Muilla maritima, Six stamens surround a stout pistil . Their anthers can be green, blue or purple.
Quercus wislizeni var. frutescens, Leaves to 2 inches long, somewhat stiff, glossy on both sides.  Leaf edges vary a lot, even on the same tree.
Quercus wislizeni var. frutescens, Thin scales on acorn cap.
Quercus wislizeni var. frutescens, Male catkins release pollen in the spring.  Female flowers are tiny, found in the joints of leaf stems.
Lilium parryi, Lemon-yellow lily flowers point sideways, featuring large orange/brown anthers , a green-tinged center and a strong fragrance.
Lilium parryi, Early plants photosynthesize from leaves that don't even have stems, building up energy for more growth next year.
Lilium parryi, It takes many years before a plant will produce multiple flowers.  Flowers appear above whorled leaves.
